<div align="center">‡º∫‚ú¶ ‚ô§ ‚ú¶‡ºª</div>
<div align="left">
&nbsp;<br />
<b>Director:</b> John <b>Terlesky</b><br />
<b>Written by:</b> Lukas <b>Reiter</b></p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
<img loading="lazy" data-attachment-id="39864" data-permalink="https://blacklistdeclassified.net/%f0%9f%94%b4-ye-olde-photo-workshoppe/a6bbb4ac-ea8b-46e1-a837-03dd518422a8/" data-orig-file="https://blacklistdeclassified.files.wordpress.com/2020/04/a6bbb4ac-ea8b-46e1-a837-03dd518422a8-e1585921615490.jpeg" data-orig-size="655,393" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;1585899415&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;1&quot;}" data-image-title="A6BBB4AC-EA8B-46E1-A837-03DD518422A8" data-image-description="" data-medium-file="https://blacklistdeclassified.files.wordpress.com/2020/04/a6bbb4ac-ea8b-46e1-a837-03dd518422a8-e1585921615490.jpeg?w=300" data-large-file="https://blacklistdeclassified.files.wordpress.com/2020/04/a6bbb4ac-ea8b-46e1-a837-03dd518422a8-e1585921615490.jpeg?w=655" src="https://blacklistdeclassified.files.wordpress.com/2020/04/a6bbb4ac-ea8b-46e1-a837-03dd518422a8-e1585921615490.jpeg?w=655&#038;h=393" alt="" width="655" height="393" class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-39864" srcset="https://blacklistdeclassified.files.wordpress.com/2020/04/a6bbb4ac-ea8b-46e1-a837-03dd518422a8-e1585921615490.jpeg 655w, https://blacklistdeclassified.files.wordpress.com/2020/04/a6bbb4ac-ea8b-46e1-a837-03dd518422a8-e1585921615490.jpeg?w=150&amp;h=90 150w, https://blacklistdeclassified.files.wordpress.com/2020/04/a6bbb4ac-ea8b-46e1-a837-03dd518422a8-e1585921615490.jpeg?w=300&amp;h=180 300w" sizes="(max-width: 655px) 100vw, 655px" /><br />
&nbsp; </p>
<blockquote><p>
<b>Brief</b> (Where we‚Äôre at): When Ressler came to apologize to Liz for putting into play the search for her mother that led to her ‚Äúdeath,‚Äù Liz confided in him that Katarina is not dead but that she had staged her death to fool Red, contrary to the story Liz had earlier told Ressler and the Task Force. Meanwhile, Red still denies to Liz that ‚Äúthe woman from Paris‚Äù is her mother, even though Liz tells him Katarina had told her that she was.</p>
<p>Red‚Äôs newest adventure has to do with a forged Byzantine-style box (‚Äúcasket‚Äù) he and Dembe had stolen thinking it was authentic. He was able to enlist the Task Force to find the forger, Victoria Fenberg (Blacklister #137), the daughter of a family that had cashed in by manufacturing opioids that killed the son of a man, Richard Vitaris, who wants justice. To help Vitaris sue her father, Victoria has used her skills as a forger to replace, one by one, the valuable works of art in her parents‚Äô considerable collection with her copies, selling the originals on the black market. </p>
<p>Red was able to track down the original of his casket from a friend of Victoria‚Äôs. But the casket is one of a set of six, and Red is due to meet up with the owners of the other five. Together, the value of the set is expected to be ‚Äúobscene, if not flagrant.‚Äù</p>
<p>Meanwhile, Aram has begun to have misgivings about his relationship with Elodie Radcliffe, a thrill-seeker whose husband is on life support. Not only does Elodie like to lure Aram into doing things that are unethical and sometimes illegal but she has hinted that it might better if her husband had died. The thought has crossed Aram‚Äôs mind as well and his struggle over whether to break up with Elodie reflects his own inner turmoil.
</p></blockquote>
<p>&nbsp; </p>
<h3>‚≠ï Script 7:12 Cornelius Ruck (‚Ññ 155)</h3>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
[ Lungef Jordan Island, Baltic Sea ]<br />
[ A seaplane descends from an overcast sky. Red and Dembe emerge and are greeted at the dock ]<br />
Arthur Rodman: Mr. Reddington. So pleased you made it, sir.<br />
<b>Red:</b> Ha! So am I. What a ride. You can&#8217;t imagine what it took to get here.<br />
Arthur: And might I say not a moment too soon. We are in for quite a storm. Arthur Rodman. I&#8217;m at your service.<br />
<b>Red:</b> What a place. This is lovely.<br />
Arthur: I&#8217;m sorry. I wasn&#8217;t prepared for‚Äì You were told no seconds are permitted?<br />
<b>Red:</b> Oh, no, no, Dembe won&#8217;t be staying.<br />
Dembe: Raymond, are you sure this place is secure?<br />
Arthur: Oh, you needn&#8217;t worry. The island is a safe haven. Mr. Vries, our owner, offers it to men and women such as Mr. Reddington as a place to do business or resolve disputes with absolute privacy and security.<br />
Dembe: And your property is the only one on the island, yes?<br />
Arthur: Yes. My employer provides staff, lodging, fine dining.<br />
<b>Red:</b> You should go before the sky gets any darker. Please. And don&#8217;t worry. I&#8217;ll see you here in two days, and we&#8217;ll celebrate.<br />
Dembe: I don&#8217;t trust Cassandra.<br />
<b>Red:</b> Ah. Eat a whole pizza, read a couple of great books. Maybe take the kids skating. My God, I can&#8217;t remember the last time you had a whole weekend off.<br />
Dembe: Two days, Raymond. Remember, you promised Agnes to be at the ballet.<br />
<b>Red:</b> I&#8217;ll see you Sunday.<br />
[ Hug ]<br />
<b>Red:</b> Not to worry. </p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
Arthur: All firearms will be kept in a safe until the proceedings are complete.<br />
[ Red puts his handgun in the large case ] [ Metal detector whining ]<br />
[ Red is driven to the entrance of a large, castle-like house. A woman, Cassandra Bianci, looks out a window as the car drives up ]</p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
[ Red gets out ]<br />
Cassandra: [ British accent ] There he is. In the flesh.<br />
<b>Red:</b> Hello, Cassandra. You&#8217;re looking like the best of times.<br />
Cassandra: I wasn&#8217;t sure you were going to make it.<br />
[ Cheek kisses ]<br />
<b>Red:</b> I had to come. I couldn&#8217;t let down the others.<br />
Cassandra: The others. Mm. Well, to be honest, I was hoping that part of you came for me.<br />
<b>Red:</b> [ Nods ]The best part did.<br />
Cassandra: You brought your piece?<br />
<b>Red:</b> Of course.<br />
Cassandra: [ Laughs ] Then it&#8217;s official. We have the complete set.<br />
<b>Red:</b> You&#8217;re convinced it&#8217;s the right time to sell?<br />
Cassandra: I am. But, um‚Äì Relax. Business later. I&#8217;ll lay everything out for the group tonight. </p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
[ Arthur shows Red his suite ]<br />
Arthur: We will stay out of your way during your stay, but anything you need, Mr. Reddington, don&#8217;t hesitate to ask.<br />
<b>Red:</b> Thank you, Arthur. </p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
[ Red greets another of the group, Annika Logan, in a separate room ]<br />
Anika: Think it&#8217;s bugged?<br />
<b>Red:</b> Annika, your brow is already furrowed.<br />
Annika: [ Laughs ] [ Island accent ] I swept my whole room‚Äì the basket, the vents. It appears clean.<br />
<b>Red:</b> That&#8217;s a relief.<br />
Annika: Mm. You bring it? Hmm. I brought it. I didn&#8217;t want to touch it, but‚Äì<br />
<b>Red:</b> [ Laughs ] Same old Annika. You&#8217;ve been reading ghost stories.<br />
Annika: Not ghost stories‚Äì news stories. It came from a tomb, right? The original dig was in Turkey‚Äì<br />
<b>Red:</b> Give me a hug.<br />
Annika: Three of the archaeologists are dead‚Äì<br />
[ Hug, cheek kiss ]<br />
Annika: ‚Äìone pancreatic cancer, one suicide, one heart disease.<br />
<b>Red:</b> You think the caskets we stole gave an archaeologist pancreatic cancer?<br />
Annika: They are cursed. [ Nebulizer hisses ]<br />
<b>Red:</b> I believe you. Well, I believe you believe you.<br />
Annika: Mm-hmm.<br />
<b>Red:</b> That innate sense of danger is what drove you to become perhaps the single best security expert I know.<br />
Annika: I&#8217;m right. Don&#8217;t touch it.<br />
<b>Red:</b> [ Chuckles ] Have you seen the others?<br />
Annika: Mm, just Margo. You think <i>I</i> haven&#8217;t changed? [ Chuckles ] Come on. She&#8217;s exactly where you&#8217;d think she&#8217;d be. </p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
[ A gaming room. Joko Kozinski holds a stopwatch ]<br />
Joko: [ Chuckles ] [ Slavic accent ] Ready, Margo? 30 seconds. Go!<br />
[ Placed in front of Margo, a heavy-set woman, are five pad locks and by each a shot of vodka. She goes to work ]<br />
Joko: Ah. Know what I&#8217;m thinking, Margo?<br />
[ Margo finishes unlocking the first lock, drinks the first shot ]<br />
Joko: I&#8217;m thinking of all the ways I&#8217;m going to be spending your moneys, yes?<br />
Margo: [ Chuckles ]<br />
[ Two more locks, two more shots ]<br />
Joko: No, no.<br />
Margot: [ Chuckles ]<br />
[ Two more ]<br />
Joko: No, no, no, no, no!<br />
[ Margo finishes the last lock, doffs the last shot ]<br />
Margo: Boo-yah!<br />
Joko: [ Grunts ] </p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
[ Red enters ]<br />
<b>Red:</b> I can name three other can openers who could crack those locks. Only one could do it in 30 seconds, and none could do it after a half pint of aquavit.<br />
Margo: Reddington, you dapper dog.<br />
<b>Red:</b> Margo, you&#8217;re a Viking.<br />
Margo: 5 grand says I can do it again in 20.<br />
[ Cheek kiss ]<br />
<b>Red:</b> No dice.<br />
[ Hug ]<br />
<b>Red:</b> I came here to [ kiss smack ] make money, not give it away.<br />
[ Mahmoud Iqbal enters ]<br />
Mahmoud: [ South Asian accent ] Good evening, Margo.<br />
Margo: [ Loudly ] Hello, Mahmoud.<br />
<b>Red:</b> Mahmoud, your hearing has gotten worse?<br />
Mahmoud: Oh, it&#8217;s not all gone. But soon.<br />
<b>Red:</b> I&#8217;m terribly sorry.<br />
Mahmoud: You&#8217;re kind. But when I decided to blow things up for a living, I knew there&#8217;d be occupational hazards.<br />
<b>Red:</b> Tell me, did I detect a chill in the air from the two of you? Are you on again or off again? </p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
[ Door opens. Cassandra enters ]<br />
<b>Red:</b> Ah.<br />
Cassandra: Welcome, everyone. Thank you for coming.<br />
[ The others seat themselves on couches which face each other ]<br />
Cassandra: I hope after what you&#8217;re about to hear, you&#8217;ll decide that it has been worth it. Let&#8217;s talk business. It&#8217;s been just under three years since I first went to Reddington, told him about the caskets, asked him to fund the job‚Äì<br />
Joko: You have buyer or not?<br />
Margo: Let her talk.<br />
Cassandra: I want to say we did the right thing. No legitimate fence would&#8217;ve touched what we had. Every art crime cop in every continent was watching. The right thing to do was split it and wait.<br />
Annika: And you think it&#8217;s been long enough?<br />
Cassandra: I do. We&#8217;ve seen a number of high-profile thefts this year. The FBI, INTERPOL, they&#8217;re busy elsewhere. It&#8217;s time to move.<br />
Joko: Who&#8217;s the buyer?<br />
Cassandra: A collector, with a particular interest in Byzantine art. I did some research and floated the idea last month.<br />
Annika: You should&#8217;ve asked us first.<br />
Mahmoud: I agree.<br />
<b>Red:</b> I don&#8217;t. As the architect, it&#8217;s Cassandra&#8217;s right to explore a next move.<br />
Cassandra: Everything was done anonymously. He has no idea who we are, but he is on his way, and weather permitting, he should be here this time tomorrow.<br />
Margo: What kinda bread we baking?<br />
Cassandra: Ah, it&#8217;s hard to know. Each individual piece could be worth a few million, but the complete set increases the potential number to maybe‚Äì<br />
Joko: 75.<br />
Cassandra: No, that&#8217;s high.<br />
Joko: Come on. The Blue Wittelsbach-Graff Diamond went for over $23 mil. The Qianlong vase went for 53, or maybe you think I&#8217;m too dumb to do my homework.<br />
Mahmoud: Take it easy.<br />
Joko: Easy? The five of you got 18% each. That&#8217;s even cut for each specialty. But me, I&#8217;m just a goon with a gun, so I only get 10? No way I&#8217;m letting you undersell and cut my take even more.<br />
Annika: Keep your voices down.<br />
Cassandra: Nobody wants to undersell‚Äì<br />
Joko: You know what? Rules say we don&#8217;t sell unless it&#8217;s unanimous, so maybe I don&#8217;t agree to anything until my cut is even!<br />
<b>Red:</b> That&#8217;s enough, Joko. You got 10% because you came in late, not because anyone here undervalues your contribution. As far as I&#8217;m concerned, the goon with the gun, he&#8217;s the real operator. He&#8217;s the one who has to handle himself under pressure when things go sideways. He&#8217;s the one everyone else has to rely on. The goon with the gun doesn&#8217;t do his job, there is no job. We needed you. Nobody&#8217;s ever said otherwise except maybe you. At the end of the day, you accepted your cut, and it&#8217;s done. So, let&#8217;s all take a breath and remember we&#8217;re friends.<br />
Margo: I vote we sell.<br />
Annika: Agreed. The sooner the better.<br />
Mahmoud: Agreed.<br />
<b>Red:</b> Then I make five.<br />
[ Joko is displeased, takes his time ]<br />
Joko: [ Reluctantly ] Agreed.<br />
Margo: [ Chuckles ]</p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
[ They lay the nesting caskets out on a table, from largest to smallest, and admire them ]<br />
Annika: Holy Mary Mother of God, protect me now and always.<br />
Cassandra: Margo, yours is the last. It&#8217;s beautiful.<br />
[ Blood drips from Margo‚Äôs nose ]<br />
Cassandra: Margo. Your nose.<br />
[ The scene through Margo‚Äôs eyes becomes blurred and distorted ]<br />
<b>Red:</b> [ Echoing ] You should sit down.<br />
[ Margo collapses. Red kneels next to her, takes her head in his hands ]<br />
<b>Red:</b> Margo! Margo. Can you hear me?</p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
[ Red and Joko carry Margo‚Äôs body into a storage room and lay her down on a steel table ]<br />
<b>Red:</b> I&#8217;ll ask Mahmoud if Margo has any family, and if so, I&#8217;ll see that they get her remains. Grab a tablecloth there.<br />
[ Red looks at Margo‚Äôs fingernails which are speckled with blood ]<br />
Joko: What do you think happened to her?<br />
[ Red checks the inside of Margot‚Äôs lip and the whites of her eyes. They, too, are blood-splotched ]<br />
Joko: What is it? What do you see? </p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
[ The living room ]<br />
Annika: It was the curse!<br />
[ Annika‚Äôs nebulizer hisses ]<br />
Cassandra: Annika, please, that&#8217;s not helpful right now.<br />
Annika: Y-You think I&#8217;m kidding? Margo was number four.  Four bodies connected to these caskets in the three years since they were found!<br />
[ Red and Joko enter ]<br />
Joko: She said stop it.<br />
<b>Red:</b> Everyone, just try to calm down.<br />
Mahmoud: What could&#8217;ve happened?<br />
Joko: Come on. Are you serious? I&#8217;ll tell you what happened. Diabetes. Hypertension‚Äì<br />
Cassandra: You hardly knew her.<br />
Joko: I don&#8217;t have to know her. Look at her. Morbidly overweight, probably alcoholic. Did she smoke?<br />
Mahmoud: Yes, but‚Äì<br />
Joko: Then the question isn&#8217;t why it happened. It&#8217;s why it didn&#8217;t happen sooner.<br />
<b>Red:</b> All right, Joko, you made your point. Margo could crack a bank vault in less than eight minutes under withering pressure. She had ice water in her veins. Okay, she didn&#8217;t make healthy choices, but this had nothing to do with stress or hypertension or a curse.<br />
[ Annika‚Äôs nebulizer hisses ]<br />
Cassandra: You think somebody killed her.<br />
Annika: Why? Who would do that?<br />
<b>Red:</b> Someone who stands to gain from her death.<br />
Cassandra: That could be any one of us. Before, it was a six-way split. Now it&#8217;s only five.<br />
Mahmoud: Perhaps, but only one of us was complaining about the size of their percentage.<br />
Joko: You think I killed your girlfriend?<br />
Mahmoud: She wasn&#8217;t my girlfriend.<br />
Joko: That&#8217;s right. You two broke up, so maybe you killed her. Maybe you can&#8217;t handle idea of her shacking up with someone new.<br />
Mahmoud: Go to hell!<br />
<b>Red:</b> Mahmoud, look at me. We are genuinely sorry for your loss. But the truth is, we don&#8217;t have enough evidence to start accusing each other of homicide. I suggest we all turn in early and look at this with fresh eyes in the morning.<br />
Annika: What about Margo&#8217;s casket?<br />
Cassandra: If everyone agrees, I&#8217;ll hold onto it for now.<br />
<b>Red:</b> We do. Everyone else, take yours with you. We&#8217;ll reconvene here at 7:00 a.m. </p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
[ Red knocks on a door. Cassandra opens it ]<br />
Cassandra: Do you remember what happened the last time you knocked on my door at 2:00 a.m.?<br />
<b>Red:</b> Yes, you shot at me.<br />
Cassandra: I thought you were someone else.<br />
<b>Red:</b> You thought I was your husband.<br />
Cassandra: I like committing crimes of passion. Want to commit one now?<br />
<b>Red:</b> I had something a bit more frigid in mind. </p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
[ Cassandra and Red enter the room where Margo‚Äôs body is ]<br />
Cassandra: Petechial hemorrhages?<br />
<b>Red:</b> Broken blood vessels in her eyes. Also on the inside of her lips and underneath her fingernails.<br />
Cassandra: That means she was poisoned?<br />
<b>Red:</b> Not definitively, no, but it certainly suggests it. We won&#8217;t know for sure until we open her up.<br />
Cassandra: What?<br />
<b>Red:</b> We need towels‚Äì tongs, and a ladle. Doesn&#8217;t matter what size.<br />
Cassandra: Boy, you really know how to show a girl a good time. Tell me, do you do autopsies during all your dates, or am I special?<br />
[ Red cuts into Margo‚Äôs belly with a knife ]<br />
Cassandra: I never heard from you after Marseilles. Was a perfect job. An even more perfect four days together at <i>H√¥tel de la Mer.</i><br />
<b>Red:</b> Can I have a towel?<br />
Cassandra: Raymond. I&#8217;ve walked away from Marco. From everything. I thought you would, too.<br />
<b>Red:</b> I was going to. Till I found out we took nearly $40 million from that vault, not 30. You&#8217;re either very bad at math or very good at lying.<br />
Cassandra: I&#8217;m good at both. What I&#8217;m terrible at is life.<br />
<b>Red:</b> Another towel.<br />
Cassandra: [ Sighs ] After Marseilles, I heard about a job in Lisbon. Big score, but it came with a big overhead. Tunneling gear, commercial grade, the works. I thought about bringing it to you, but I couldn&#8217;t. You say you walked away because I took the money, but I took it because you&#8217;d already walked away.<br />
[ Red pries open the cut in Margo‚Äôs belly with the tongs ]<br />
<b>Red:</b> Can you hold that?<br />
Cassandra: I shouldn&#8217;t have done it, but I was hurt, and‚Äì I regret it. You have no reason to believe me, but I do.<br />
<b>Red:</b> Tell me about Lisbon.<br />
Cassandra: Uh‚Äì I invested everything I had and even some I didn&#8217;t have. And then, at the last minute, just two days before we were set to move, the museum shipped the piece back to New York, made a secret deal to trade exhibits, and‚Äì that was it. I lost my entire investment.<br />
<b>Red:</b> Why are you telling me this?<br />
Cassandra: You asked.<br />
<b>Red:</b> You brought it up. Why?<br />
Cassandra: Because‚Äì I&#8217;ve had a run of bad luck lately, and I&#8217;ve been thinking a lot about why.<br />
<b>Red:</b> You sound like Annika.<br />
Cassandra: [ Scoffs ] It&#8217;s no accident that things went wrong when I burned what we had. I would do anything to take it back, to go back to that suite at <i>H√¥tel de la Mer.</i><br />
<b>Red:</b> The ladle. The ladle.<br />
[ Cassandra hands him the ladle. Red uses it dip into open cut ]<br />
<b>Red:</b> [ Sighs ] She bled to death internally. Must be half her blood supply.<br />

<h2>üî¥ Script 7:13 Newton Purcell (‚Ññ 144)</h2>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
Program air date: 4/3/2020 in the US<br />
Permalink: <a href="https://wp.me/pDKwi-an3" rel="nofollow">https://wp.me/pDKwi-an3</a><br />

<img loading="lazy" data-attachment-id="39907" data-permalink="https://blacklistdeclassified.net/%f0%9f%94%b4-ye-olde-photo-workshoppe/fcecd7a6-e2db-42ce-b914-1533f143804c/" data-orig-file="https://blacklistdeclassified.files.wordpress.com/2020/04/fcecd7a6-e2db-42ce-b914-1533f143804c-e1586538141448.jpeg" data-orig-size="655,369" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;1586498209&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;1&quot;}" data-image-title="FCECD7A6-E2DB-42CE-B914-1533F143804C" data-image-description="" data-medium-file="https://blacklistdeclassified.files.wordpress.com/2020/04/fcecd7a6-e2db-42ce-b914-1533f143804c-e1586538141448.jpeg?w=300" data-large-file="https://blacklistdeclassified.files.wordpress.com/2020/04/fcecd7a6-e2db-42ce-b914-1533f143804c-e1586538141448.jpeg?w=655" src="https://blacklistdeclassified.files.wordpress.com/2020/04/fcecd7a6-e2db-42ce-b914-1533f143804c-e1586538141448.jpeg?w=655&#038;h=369" alt="" width="655" height="369" class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-39907" srcset="https://blacklistdeclassified.files.wordpress.com/2020/04/fcecd7a6-e2db-42ce-b914-1533f143804c-e1586538141448.jpeg 655w, https://blacklistdeclassified.files.wordpress.com/2020/04/fcecd7a6-e2db-42ce-b914-1533f143804c-e1586538141448.jpeg?w=150&amp;h=85 150w, https://blacklistdeclassified.files.wordpress.com/2020/04/fcecd7a6-e2db-42ce-b914-1533f143804c-e1586538141448.jpeg?w=300&amp;h=169 300w" sizes="(max-width: 655px) 100vw, 655px" /><br />
&nbsp; </p>
<blockquote><p>
<b>Brief</b> (Where we‚Äôre at): In the last episode, Red hooked up with an old flame, Cassandra Bianchi, with whom he had had a relationship before having had to leave her when he learned that Liz‚Äôs husband Tom ‚Äúwas not who he appeared to be.‚Äù Red and Cassandra were two of six friends ~ all experts in various fields of criminal activity ~ who had come together on a remote island in the Baltic Sea, each bringing one of the set of Byzantine caskets originally from Turkey which they had stolen. The value of the set would be much greater than that of the individual pieces. At the time they were stolen, the set had been too hot to try to sell, but time had elapsed and the time was ripe. </p>
<p>But then, one of the members of the group, then another, were murdered and the others ~ except for Red and Cassandra ~ also died. That‚Äôs when Cassandra told Red that she had been betrayed in a deal in which an American operative had been looking for one of the boxes because it contained a microdot (an extremely reduced document) with a list of names of Turkish operatives. But the Turks wanted the list, too, and had hired an American traitor to get the list for them. The American they hired turned out to be masquerading as the butler of the venue, introduced first as Arthur Rodman, but Red recognized him as Cornelius Ruck (Blacklister #155). Red and Cassandra were able to overcome Ruck and his operatives and made plans to go off together, now that Liz was no longer in danger. But first, Red had one more obligation: to watch Liz‚Äôs daughter Agnes dance in ‚ÄúSleeping Beauty.‚Äù </p>
<p>Red and Cassandra watched Agnes‚Äôs performance from the wings. But, at the last minute, Cassandra changed her mind and said she would be leaving because: ‚ÄúI saw you watching, how you looked. You may have come into her life out of obligation, but you&#8217;re staying in it for love.‚Äù After Cassandra left, Liz came over to thank <b>Red:</b> </p>
<blockquote><p>
Liz: ‚Ä¶ Thank you, by the way, for the intel on the Turkish agents. You know, you were right when you recently told me that, um, it&#8217;s been difficult since Tom, but that I have Agnes, and I should be looking forward and not back.<br />
<b>Red:</b> And that you deserve a bigger life.<br />
Liz: [ Sighs ] I agree. I do. But so do you.<br />
<b>Red:</b> [ Sighs ] I don&#8217;t know how to do that.<br />
Liz: That makes two of us. ‚Ä¶ Thanks again for coming. It means a lot.<br />
<b>Red:</b> To me, too.<br />
[ Red begins to walk away ]<br />
Liz: Hey.<br />
[ Red turns to look back ]<br />
Liz: We may not have bigger lives, but we have each other.
</p></blockquote>
</blockquote>

<blockquote><p>
<b>Brief</b> (Where we‚Äôre at): Red had to bail out his ever-unreliable tracker Glen Carter after Glen messed up the order for a black market tritium-enriched vehicle worth $12M. The truck ended up being the prize in a contest pitting Glen against the two time winner, Pastor Ritzen. Unbeknownst to Glen, with whom Red has ‚Äúa history‚Äù and an odd co-dependence, Red was able to buy off the good pastor with a Mercedes. With another Mercedes (a snazzy sportster) given to Glen as a reward for his ‚Äúwin,‚Äù the product placement value must have beenüí∞pricelessüí∞ </p>
<p>Meanwhile, Aram‚Äôs relationship with the thrill-seeking Elodie Radcliffe took a turned when Elodie‚Äôs husband Charles died. He had been paralyzed for months and unable to speak after being selected as the unlucky one at a gathering of risk-takers at a venue called <i>Les Fleurs du Mal</i>, hosted by one Thelonius Prackett [Episode 7:3, Blacklister #151]. Elodie and Aram had been having an affair under the shadow of Charles‚Äôs condition and Aram wants children. But, during the wake for Charles, Aram discovered the papers for a pre-nuptial agreement. Elodie had told Aram there wasn‚Äôt one. Now he knows she will inherit $12M under the agreement and wonders why she lied to him. </p>
<p>Liz has not given up her determination to learning about Red‚Äôs past. After an FBI Contact in the Hoover Building came up short, he gave her the name of an private investigator. Liz had to dig out cash for payment from Tom‚Äôs wooden ‚Äúgo box‚Äù ‚Äì the one carved with the mysterious sign resembling the scar on Liz‚Äôs wrist ‚Äì for the cash for payment. She met up with the P.I. and gave her the cash and a folder on Ilya Koslov, the former KGB operative whose history with both Red and Liz‚Äôs mother ~ the infamous former KGB spy Katarina Rostova ~ stretches back to the Cold War. Liz knows that Katarina, though in hiding, is still alive after having staged her own assassination to deceive Red and put him and others hunting her at bay.
</p></blockquote>
<p>&nbsp; </p>
<h3>‚≠ï Script 7:14 Twamie Ullulaq (‚Ññ 144)</h3>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
[ Red and Dembe are driving a Range Rover along a highway on the southern coast of Alaska ]<br />
<b>Red:</b> How long has it been since we lost contact with the driver?<br />
Dembe: 18 hours. Any chance we will find the cargo intact?<br />
<b>Red:</b> That would take incredible luck. And the only time I have ever been lucky in Alaska was when I was bumped from behind at an ice bar in Fairbanks. I stumbled into the arms of a lovely Nordic princess. Literally, she was a princess in Norway. We flew straight to her castle outside Bergen and watched the Northern Lights till dawn. Otherwise, Alaska&#8217;s shown me all the mercy of a Greek tragedy.<br />
[ The locator on the GPS device is beeping ]<br />
‚ãò‚ãô<br />
[ The vehicle pulls over and they get out ]<br />
Dembe: Strange. According to the tracker, we should be right on top of the containers.<br />
[ They look around and see nothing. They are next to a body of water. Red scans the forested area then looks at the water. Beneath the surface are the outlines of several submerged semi-trailer trucks ]<br />
<b>Red:</b> Looks like it&#8217;s time to cue the Greek chorus, Dembe. </p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
[ Red is in a commercial-style kitchen preparing salmon. Aram has come to see him ]<br />
Aram: Elodie lied about not having a prenup. And now that her husband&#8217;s dead, she stands to inherit millions.<br />
<b>Red:</b> The way you described her husband&#8217;s condition, it sounds more like a mercy killing.<br />
Aram: Maybe, but he didn&#8217;t have a medical directive, and she couldn&#8217;t have know what was going on inside of his head.<br />
<b>Red:</b> You mean like dreams and memories. Maybe even a deep and abiding love for his betrothed.<br />
Aram: Exactly.<br />
<b>Red:</b> A love so deep that he would have preferred that Elodie end his life so that she could move on with hers. If only he had the power to tell her.<br />
Aram: No. Wait. Wait, what?<br />
<b>Red:</b> How can I help you, Aram?<br />
Aram: I want to know if Elodie killed her husband. If she did, I have to arrest her. I&#8217;m definitely‚Äì I&#8217;m definitely breaking up with her. But I don&#8217;t really know yet, But I need to know, you know?<br />
[ Liz enters ]<br />
Liz: Need to know what?<br />
Aram: Oh, um‚Äì whether Elodie killed her husband.<br />
Liz: And you want Reddington&#8217;s help?<br />
<b>Red:</b> Get a blood sample from the body before it&#8217;s buried, and I&#8217;ll have it tested, no questions asked.<br />
Liz: Or ‚Äì crazy idea‚Äì you could let the police investigate.<br />
Aram: I should go and let the two of you do whatever it is you two do.<br />
<b>Red:</b> Do you know why I&#8217;m preparing this salmon?<br />
Aram: If this is about your libido, I&#8217;m‚Äì I&#8217;m good.<br />
Liz: W-Where are we? Why are we here?<br />
<b>Red:</b> It&#8217;s for a celebratory meal when the case is solved.<br />
Liz: And what case is that?<br />
<b>Red:</b> I&#8217;ve been robbed. Trucks of mine have been stolen. Precious cargo has gone missing.<br />
Liz: You want us to find your trucks.<br />
<b>Red:</b> I found the trucks. Sunk in a lake in the Alaska Triangle.<br />
Aram: Wait, the Triangle&#8217;s real?<br />
<b>Red:</b> I don&#8217;t want you to find my trucks. I want you to solve one of life&#8217;s great mysteries.<br />
Liz: The Alaska Triangle.<br />
Aram: A place where some people go and never return. Supposedly 16,000 in the last 50 years.<br />
Liz: [ Scoffs ] Okay. That can&#8217;t be true.<br />
<b>Red:</b> The question isn&#8217;t whether they&#8217;ve disappeared. It&#8217;s why. Find the people who stole my trucks and you may get the answer. </p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
[ The Post Office ] [ Liz and Aram brief the task force ]<br />
Aram: This is former U.S. House Majority Leader Hale Boggs. Now, in 1972, his twin-engine Cessna vanished somewhere between Juneau and Anchorage. The nation&#8217;s largest search-and-rescue mission was mounted. The Coast Guard, Civil Air Patrol, the Navy. All scoured the area for months, but no trace of Boggs&#8217; plane was ever found.<br />
Liz: He was lost in a section of the state known as the Alaska Triangle.<br />

Aram: Your immunity agreement required full disclosure about any and all crimes involved in Prackett&#8217;s ventures. If you fail to disclose one, the deal will be torn up, and you will go to prison. Why were you really at her house?<br />
Eaton: Because now she can pay me what she owes.<br />
Aram: Because of the prenup. Wait. Wait, why does she owe you money?<br />
Eaton: I remember you. From The Defiance.<br />
Aram: What did you do for her?<br />
Eaton: [ Chuckles quietly ] You don&#8217;t want to know. </p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
[ The metal shed ]<br />
Lussier: You were gonna let him kill me.<br />
Park: He was bluffing.<br />
Lussier: He was right about coincidences. They don&#8217;t happen here. You need to have a purpose to come here. I know yours was to kill me.<br />
[ Door opens. Wyatt enters pointing a gun and throws handcuffs to Park and Lussier ]<br />
Wyatt: Put them on.<br />
Park: Or what? You&#8217;re gonna shoot us? You want us to wear these, you&#8217;re gonna have to put them on us yourself.<br />
Wyatt: You&#8217;re too feisty for your own good. Anyone ever tell you that?<br />
[ He tries to put the handcuffs on Park ]<br />
Park: All the time.<br />
[ ‚ö°Ô∏èFight ‚ö°Ô∏è] [ Grunting ] [ Park wins easily, leaving Wyatt unconscious, lying face down. She puts cuffs on him. Lussier gets Wyatt‚Äôs gun, which he points at Park ] [ Gun cocks ]<br />
Lussier: I know you blame me for what h-happened, but I didn&#8217;t kill her.<br />
Park: [ Recognizing him ] Lussier‚Äì?<br />
Lussier: But looks like you did come back here to die. </p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
[ The FBI field office in Anchorage ]<br />
Connor: AKRCC&#8217;s running search and rescue assets out of Elmendorf, and the state troopers have their infrared chopper in the air as we speak.<br />
Ressler: Were you able to monitor radio frequencies up here?<br />
Connor: All 406 emergency locator beacons.<br />
Ressler: She knows your protocol, so if she still has a radio, expect her to try to make contact.<br />
Liz: What about the land granted to Operation Washtub? Have you located it?<br />
Connor: We&#8217;re working on it.<br />
Ressler: Yeah, well, work harder.<br />
Connor: This mission was a mistake to begin with. Park got herself into this situation, and it&#8217;s an unfortunate one, but these people, the ones who are searching for her, they&#8217;re the very best at what they do, and they will do whatever they can to find her. Now, if you&#8217;ll excuse me, we got a location on the camp.<br />
[ Connor leaves ]<br />
Ressler: What is it with her and Park?<br />
Liz: Park&#8217;s history here is‚Äì complicated.<br />
Ressler: Meaning?<br />
Liz: Park made mistakes. Connor covered on the promise Park would not return.<br />
Ressler: Covered? What did she do?<br />
Liz: You have a black sheep in your family. Let&#8217;s just say Park has a black sheep of her own. </p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
[ The encampment ] [ Men speaking indistinctly ] [ Lussier cracks open the door of the metal shed and looks out ]<br />
Park:  You&#8217;ll never make it.<br />
Lussier: Really? Watch me.<br />
Park: I stand a better chance.<br />
Lussier: I doubt it. Seeing as how I&#8217;m the one with the gun.<br />
Park: You&#8217;re lucky if it&#8217;s 20 degrees right now. Once the sun drops behind that ridge, it&#8217;ll fall below zero, and that&#8217;s before dark.<br />
Lussier: I&#8217;m not letting you out.<br />
Park: I know we&#8217;re on the south side of the Bagley Icefield. I also know if we can get to Quill Creek, it&#8217;ll point us toward the highway. You, on the other hand, you&#8217;re a junkie lost in the woods. A nobody from nowhere. You said so yourself.<br />
Lussier: Why would you h-help me?<br />
Park: I&#8217;m helping myself. You&#8217;ll die out there, Edward. But if you leave me, I&#8217;ll die in here.<br />
[ Lussier pauses, then hands her the keys ]<br />
Park: The bullets.<br />
Lussier: Hmm?<br />
Park: I don&#8217;t care if you carry the gun, but I carry the bullets. Think of it as the first step towards you and I trusting each other.<br />
[ Together they sneak out of the metal shed ] [ Men speaking indistinctly in distance ] </p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
Gerrit: Mr. Ullulaq, we have a situation.<br />
[ They walk over to the shed ]<br />
Wyatt: [ Groans ] I&#8217;m sorry. I never saw it coming.<br />
Ullulaq: Well, they couldn&#8217;t have gotten that far. Take Gerrit with you. Radio the camp when you find their footpath. </p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
Park: As far as I&#8217;m concerned, there&#8217;s no end to the charges they could bring against you, but murder is the only one that matters.<br />
Lussier: I know you think that, but you&#8217;re not gonna do anything about it.<br />
Park: You killed my mother.<br />
Lussier: You tell anybody, I&#8217;ll go public. I know what happened at Anchorage Correctional. Yeah. How you put J. Yost in a wheelchair. Yeah. I know about those cops you paid off. I know how you, uh, held Wade Leek at gunpoint. And I know you‚Äì you broke the law in enough different ways in order to try and find me that you friends at the FBI had to cover it up.<br />
Park: We need to keep moving.<br />
Lussier: You hear me?<br />
Park: It&#8217;s getting late.<br />
Lussier: You turn me in, I&#8217;ll tell them everything. Every gory detail. No, you&#8217;re not gonna say anything to nobody.<br />
[ Lussier has been following Park a couple meters behind. He sees a large branch and picks it up. He runs toward her with the branch raised to strike he. She is unaware ]<br />
Lussier: &#8216;Cause you&#8217;re not walking out of these woods‚Äì<br />
[ Lussier steps in a bear trap‚ö°Ô∏è]<br />
Lussier: Aah! Oh!<br />
Park: Don&#8217;t move!<br />
[ Park comes to Lussier‚Äòs aid. She tries to pull the jaws of the trap apart ]<br />
Lussier: [ Screaming ]<br />
Park: Hold on! Hold on!<br />
Lussier: Pull! Harder! Harder!<br />
Park: I&#8217;m trying! I can&#8217;t!<br />
Lussier: I&#8217;m begging you! Please! Please!<br />
Park: I&#8217;ll be back.<br />
Lussier: No. Don&#8217;t leave me. You can&#8217;t! I&#8217;m begging you. Please. </p>
<blockquote><p>
<b>Flashback: </b><br />
Park‚Äôs Mother: [ Begging ] Please. Please. Sweetie, I&#8217;m begging. Please. Please.<br />
[ Alina Park is a young girl. Tearfully, she shakes her head ‚Äòno‚Äô ]
</p></blockquote>
<p>Lussier: I&#8217;ll die here!<br />
Park: I can&#8217;t open the trap. Not on my own. I&#8217;ll get help, and I will come back.<br />
Lussier: And if they get here first?<br />
[ Park gives him the bullets ]<br />
Park: You only got six. Aim carefully.<br />
[ She runs off ]</p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
[ The encampment ]<br />
Gerrit: [ On radio phone ] Twamie, we got a situation.<br />
Ullulaq: You find them?<br />
Gerrit: Scouts radioed. We got a breach. Feds on the south ridge.<br />
[ üí•üî•üí• Explosions üí•üî•üí• ] [ üí•üî•üí• ]<br />

[ üí•üí•üí• Gunfight üí•üí•üí• üí•üí•üí• ]<br />
[ Ullulaq aims his shotgun ]<br />

[ Twamie Ullulaq freezes. He turns around and sees Liz ]</p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
[ Indistinct shouting ] [ Indistinct conversations ]<br />
[ An FBI TAC Agent comes up to Ressler ]<br />
TAC Agent: Sir. She&#8217;s not here, sir.<br />
‚ãò‚ãô<br />
[ Liz walks up to Ullulaq ]<br />

Ullulaq: Why would I want to do that?<br />

Liz: Your men have her or are looking for her. Either way, you&#8217;ve been in communication. Where are they?<br />
‚ãò‚ãô<br />
[ Gerrit walks up to Lussier. Others follow Gerrit with Park ]<br />
Gerrit: Now, that&#8217;s a piss-poor hiding spot.<br />
[ Lussier gets the gun ]<br />
Gerrit: Put it down. Slowly.<br />
Lussier: Okay. Okay, wait, wait. Just wait!<br />
[ Lussier puts the gun down and raises his hands ]<br />
Lussier: All right? Please. I can help you.<br />
Gerrit: I don&#8217;t think you&#8217;re gonna be much help at all.<br />
Lussier: No, listen. I have information about your FBI agent there. You know, things she&#8217;s done. You could use her to barter with the police, cut a deal.<br />
Gerrit: We don&#8217;t have orders to make deals. Our order&#8217;s to make examples out of you.<br />
Lussier: Wait, hold on. I&#8217;m telling you, she&#8217;s a dirty cop.<br />
Gerrit:  Not anymore she&#8217;s not.<br />
[ Gerrit turns to shoot Park ]<br />
Ressler: FBI! Put the gun down!<br />
[ üí•üí• Gunshots üí•üí•] [ Gerrit falls behind a tree trunk ] [ Several of Gerrit‚Äôs group are shot ]<br />
[ Liz runs up to Park ]<br />
Liz: You okay?<br />
[ Gerrit rises and is about to shoot Park ]<br />
Park: Keen!<br />
[ Lussier shoots üí• Gerrit before he can shoot. Lussier drops the gun and puts his hands up, surrendering ]<br />
Lussier: [ Shivering ]<br />
[ Park stares at Lussier ]</p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
[ The FBI field office ]<br />
Liz: You okay?<br />
[ Lussier is wheeled by in a wheelchair ]<br />
Park: Better than him. My mother&#8217;s boyfriend from Anchorage.<br />
Liz: The one you&#8217;ve been hunting all these years. How is that possible? Did you know he was here?<br />
Park: Of course not.<br />
Liz: How did you two end up in the same place together?<br />
Park: I think we both know the answer to that. </p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
[ Aram leads Elodie through the war room of the Post Office ]<br />

[ Aram opens a door to a room where Wilbur Eaton sits ]<br />
Elodie: What&#8217;s he doing here?<br />
Aram: Sit down.<br />
Elodie: I can explain.<br />
Aram: Explain what? That Charles didn&#8217;t find Les Fleurs du Mal? You did.<br />
Eaton: I told him about our arrangement.<br />
Elodie: There is no arrangement.<br />
Eaton: How you came to me, got me to invite your husband and made sure he was selected for the challenge.<br />
Elodie: He came to the house‚Äì<br />
Aram: Selected to die.<br />
Elodie: He wanted money. He said he would tell these lies if I didn&#8217;t give it to him.<br />
Aram: But Charles didn&#8217;t die. And then I showed up. When we insisted you go to The Defiance, you got Eaton to pick you. I thought I was saving you, but‚Äì you two had worked out a way for you to save yourself.<br />
Elodie: No. I would have died without you.<br />
Aram: No. You used me. You got me to open up to you. That&#8217;s why you kept asking about Blacklisters. To seduce me into giving you a murder weapon.<br />
Elodie: You can&#8217;t believe that. I can&#8217;t believe you would take his word over mine.<br />
Aram: Your word, then‚Äì Did you kill him?<br />
Elodie: I love you.<br />
Aram: Did you kill Charles?<br />
Elodie: No.<br />
Aram: I hope that&#8217;s true. </p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
[ Sizzling ] [ Red is cooking Shiozake, Japanese-style salted salmon, and drinking white wine ]<br />
<b>Red:</b> Agent Park.<br />
Park: You kidnapped Lussier. They found him inside your truck, didn&#8217;t they?<br />
<b>Red:</b> We can discuss that over Shiozake.<br />
Park: You orchestrated this whole thing. You put us together.<br />
<b>Red:</b> I intended on bringing you together, yes, by abducting him, not you. That was unforeseen. But in the end, it served the greater good.<br />
Park: You have no business interfering in my life.<br />
<b>Red:</b> I do when your life interferes with my business. I know about your mother and her relationship with Mr. Lussier.<br />
Park: How could you know that?<br />
<b>Red:</b> Because I must. You&#8217;re an excellent agent, Alina, and a loose cannon. I need the first, and I won&#8217;t tolerate the second.<br />
Park: So you put us together so I could, what? Exact my revenge and become less uncontrollable?<br />
<b>Red:</b> My world is filled with people seeking revenge. I can see it every time I look at them. It&#8217;s as distinct as a birthmark. But I look at you and see none of that. I don&#8217;t see a quest for vengeance. I see a smart, capable young woman filled with self-loathing, and I think if you have a debt to settle, perhaps it&#8217;s with yourself.<br />
Park: Lussier&#8217;s an addict who supports his habit through armed robbery and theft. I settled my debt with him when I gave everything I knew about his crimes to the Alaska bureau.<br />
<b>Red:</b> And the debt you owe yourself?<br />
Park: [ Sighs ] I settled that by giving them nothing about what he did to my mother. Because he‚Äì did nothing. The heroin did. They were addicts, and they were helpless to help each other. I was helpless, too.<br />
<b>Red:</b> You were a child. You couldn&#8217;t be expected to help. You shouldn&#8217;t hate yourself for that.<br />
Park: After he left, she was shaking and vomiting and doubled over in pain. I was 7. All I saw was that she was in pain, and I wanted that pain to stop. </p>
<blockquote><p>
<b>Flashback:</b><br />
Park‚Äôs Mother: Sweetie, I&#8217;m begging. Please.
</p></blockquote>
<p>Park: So I did as I was told. </p>
<blockquote><p>
<b>Flashback:</b><br />
[ Young Alina Park tightens a length of plastic tubing around her mother‚Äôs arm ]
</p></blockquote>
<p>Park: At first, she was so‚Äì happy. The pain just disappeared. And then her eyes rolled back into her head, and‚Äì she died. </p>
<blockquote><p>
<b>Flashback:</b><br />
[ Alina‚Äôs mother dies ]<br />
Young Alina: [ Crying ]
</p></blockquote>
<p>Park: She overdosed. I overdosed her. I don&#8217;t hate myself because I couldn&#8217;t help my mom. I hate myself because I killed her. </p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
[ Fort Slocum park ] [ Aram waits ]<br />
[ Bike bell dings‚ú® ] [ Brakes squeal ] [ The Hasidic man stops his bicycle. He takes the blood analysis report out of the bike basket and hands it to Aram ]<br />
Aram: Thank you.<br />
[ The man rides off. Aram unfolds the report and reads ]</p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
[ Cooper‚Äôs office ] [ Knock on door ]<br />
Cooper: Agent Park, come in. I hear congratulations are in order.<br />
Park: Thank you, sir. We got lucky, sir.<br />
Cooper: Diligence is the mother of good luck. What&#8217;s on your mind?<br />
Park: Anchorage and my past there.<br />
Cooper: I&#8217;ve read your file. I know things got a little bumpy near the end.<br />
Park: Bumpy would be a gracious choice of words. Sir, there are things that happened in Anchorage, things I did that you&#8217;re not aware of. You should be.<br />
[ Gregory Alan Isakov&#8217;s ‚ô´ ‚ÄúBerth‚Äù plays ]<br />
[ Cooper uncorks a bottle of Scotch and pours ]<br />
Cooper: So, what sort of things?<br />
[ Cooper slides a glass of Scotch to Park ]</p>
<blockquote><p>
‚ô™ Silver winged, broken English, boys they smoke<br />
Talk and joke above the water ‚ô™
</p></blockquote>
<p>[ Later, Cooper stands by Liz by the yellow staircase ] [ Above on the landing, Ressler sits next to Twamie Ullulaq, booking him ]<br />
Liz: It&#8217;s strange. I know we solved at least part of the Alaska Triangle, but after all he was promised, it&#8217;s hard not to empathize.<br />
Cooper: I&#8217;ve spoken to Agent Park‚Äì<br />
Liz: And now he&#8217;s going to prison for the rest of his life.<br />
Cooper: She told me about Anchorage. She told me you know. I&#8217;m curious as to why you didn&#8217;t feel the need to say anything to me.<br />
Liz: I didn&#8217;t say anything because I don&#8217;t think you should do anything.<br />
Cooper: She didn&#8217;t just bend the rule book. She broke it.<br />
Liz: And I can understand why you would have a hard time accepting that. But when it comes to family, it&#8217;s complicated. I know that&#8217;s true for me. You know better than anyone, I haven&#8217;t always been my best self. I don&#8217;t think any of us have. Honestly, I think you should give her the benefit of the doubt. I think in a situation like this, we should give everyone the benefit of the doubt.<br />

<blockquote><p>
<b>Brief</b> (Where we‚Äôre at): After his trucks carrying a precious cargo of smuggled ambergris ended up in the bottom of an Alaskan lake, Red aranged to deal with two problems at once: solving the mysterious disappearances in the ‚ÄúAlaskan Triangle‚Äù and arranging for Agent Alina Park to confront the man she had been searching for for years and who she held responsible for the death of her mother, her boyfriend and fellow heroin addict, Edward Lussier. In the end, after Edward saved Park‚Äôs life, she was forced to confront the fact that it was she who killed her mother, when as a child of seven, she responded to her mother‚Äôs pleas and injected her with heroin, accidentally overdosing her. </p>
<p>Park, Liz and Ressler solved the Alaska Triangle mystery after setting a trap by running one of Red‚Äôs trucks through the area. It was hijacked by a group led by Twamie Ullulaq (Blacklister #126), a Native American who had been trained in counter-insurgency by the CIA during the Cold War, only to have the promises of housing and schools that were promised evaporate when the Cold War ended. So Ullulaq‚Äôs crew had turned to highway robbery, using the skills learned from the US Government. </p>
<p>Red also helped Aram, who had discovered his girlfriend Elodie, whose husband had just died after being in a vegetative state for month, had a prenuptial agreement ~ something she had told him did not exist. This made Aram question whether Elodie had killed her husband. Aram took a blood draw from Elodie‚Äôs husband‚Äôs corpse and had it processed using Red‚Äôs contacts. The test turned out positive and Aram was forced to arrest Elodie for murder, despite the feelings they had both developed for each other.
</p></blockquote>

<p>&nbsp;<br />
[ Later; same hearing room ]<br />
Judge Borns: We are on the record. So, let me be clear ‚Äì It is not for this court to tell the FBI how to do its job or who to arrest. AUSA Horan: We believe we can win.<br />
Judge: Yes, but you face an extremely high burden. You need to prove that Mr. Kemp knew ‚Äì or he should have known ‚Äì that he was actually selling those guns to a prohibited buyer. Hmm?<br />
And don&#8217;t get me wrong, straw purchases ‚Äì serious problem in this country. There may be more than 30,000 attempted straw purchases every year ‚Äì but the seriousness of the problem does not change the requirements for what the government needs to make its case. Well, Ms. Ambers&#8217; age and the volume of the purchases ‚Äì they&#8217;re facts that certainly give me pause, but are they enough to conclude that Mr. Kemp and his associates committed a federal criminal offense? I think not. I find the evidence insufficient to sustain the charges. Therefore, in the interest of justice and judicial economy, this case is dismissed without prejudice.<br />
Cooper: May I address the court?‚Äì<br />
Judge: No, you may not. You have my ruling. The matter is sealed, and the defendant will be released. We are adjourned. </p>

Kemp: Not &#8217;cause of me. Not &#8217;cause of anything I did.<br />
<b>Red:</b> Yes, yes, of course. You dot the I&#8217;s, cross the T&#8217;s, and, in your world, those rules protect you. But in my world, there are no laws to hide behind. You can act in bad faith as long as you&#8217;re willing to face the consequences.<br />
Kemp: What consequences?<br />
<b>Red:</b> The wrath of men like me. I object to what you&#8217;re doing, and I don&#8217;t need to convince any court to agree with me. In my world, if I think you&#8217;re guilty ‚Äì I just execute sentence.<br />
Kemp: Please. Please, don&#8217;t do this.<br />
<b>Red:</b> I heard‚Äì heard someone else beg at the point of one of your guns. She said please, too. And then she was murdered. Now, I understand it can be hard to see tragedy for what it is until that tragedy befalls you or a loved one. Well, I&#8217;m here to tell you that&#8217;s happening to you. About an hour ago, a violent criminal bought one of your FineCal 9s on the street for $100, and now that criminal is going to shoot you with it. Tragic.<br />
[ Red shootsüí•üí• Kemp ]</p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
[ Ana Salgado lights a candle and adds it to the memorial to her daughter outside the entrance of the convenience store where she was murdered ]</p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
[ Liz visits Red at home ]<br />
Liz: It was Cooper. He tricked me.<br />
<b>Red:</b> You seem put out by it. Don&#8217;t be. Take it as a compliment.<br />
Liz: That he doesn&#8217;t trust me?<br />
<b>Red:</b> That he knows you&#8217;re a person of conviction and principle.<br />
Liz: A lot of good my principle did. Kemp got all of his guns.<br />
[ Red has been drinking red wine. He pours a glass for Liz ]<br />
<b>Red:</b> Yes. He got his.<br />
Liz: What did you do?<br />
<b>Red:</b> I acted on my conviction and principle.<br />
Liz: Cooper says we blur the line between right and wrong so often, we can&#8217;t see it clearly anymore. I know I can&#8217;t.<br />
<b>Red:</b> I disagree. I find you increasingly clear-eyed. I&#8217;m sorry that the Task Force had to take sides today, but it meant a great deal to me to know you were on mine.<br />
[ Red‚Äôs cellphone rings ]<br />
<b>Red:</b> Excuse me. Any news?<br />
Dembe: [ On phone ] The woman in the blue Malibu ‚Äì She&#8217;s a private eye, Raymond. Hired to learn what she can about Ilya. It was Elizabeth. She hired her. She knows you&#8217;re not Ilya and she&#8217;s been keeping it from you.<br />
[ Red eyes glare at Liz. Liz is looking down ]<br />
<b>Red:</b> I understand. [ Hangs up ] [ Sniffs ]<br />
Liz: Is everything all right?<br />
[ Red raises his glass ]<br />
<b>Red:</b> To being on the same side.<br />
[ Liz raises her glass ]<br />
Liz: At long last.</p>

<h2>üî¥ Script 7:16 Nyle Hatcher (‚Ññ 149)</h2>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
Program air date: 5/24/2020 in the US<br />
Script Permalink: <a href="https://wp.me/pDKwi-apn" rel="nofollow">https://wp.me/pDKwi-apn</a><br />
Entertainment Weekly Recap: <a href="http://bit.ly/3eB9L3a" rel="nofollow">http://bit.ly/3eB9L3a</a><br />
&nbsp; </p></div>
<div align="center">‡º∫‚ú¶ ‚ô§ ‚ú¶‡ºª</div>
<div align="left">
&nbsp;<br />
<b>Director:</b> Tessa <b>Blake</b><br />
<b>Written by:</b> Katie <b>Bockes</b></p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
<img loading="lazy" data-attachment-id="40053" data-permalink="https://blacklistdeclassified.net/%f0%9f%94%b4-ye-olde-photo-workshoppe/72ac9f28-a581-4238-8735-5104dcf48e58/" <blockquote><p>
<b>Brief</b> (Where we‚Äôre at): Once more, just as it seemed Liz and Red are on the ‚Äúsame side,‚Äù Red found out that Liz hired a private investigator to find his friend Ilya Koslov (now known as Frank Bloom). Liz has known for some time that Red is not Ilya, as she was told in a tale spun by her grandfather, Dominic Wilkinson. Ilya and Dom were both KGB operatives and both were involved in an attempt to kill Katarina Rostova, Dom‚Äôs daughter and Ilya‚Äôs friend. Katarina was also a KGB operative and infamous spy, who made enemies by joining The Cabal, a secret group of cross-national power brokers. Dom wanted Liz to think Red was Ilya, and to keep her from finding out the truth: that he (Dom), with help from Ilya, had attempted to assassinate Katarina to protect Liz (aka ‚ÄúMasha‚Äù). But Liz did find out, when she figured that her new next door neighbor and ersatz nanny was indeed her mother. After gaining Liz‚Äôs sympathy, Katarina has again gone into hiding, but not before staging her own death to fool Red. </p>
<p>But as Red was not Ilya, who was he? DNA analysis of skeletal remains proved that Liz‚Äôs father, the real Raymond Reddington, is dead. *Someone* underwent plastic surgery to assume his identity, but who? Liz intends to find out, but Ilya, who she hired a private investigator to find, has again gone into hiding. The reason why Red became Liz‚Äôs hidden benefactor, then the confidential informant for the Reddington Task Force, and increasingly her friend, remain inscrutable.</p>
<p>But one thing is clear, increasingly Liz has been inclined to see things from Red‚Äôs point of view, especially when the legal system and law enforcement fail to deliver ‚Äújustice.‚Äù This played out in Episode 7:15 Gordon Kemp (Blacklister #158) about the unscrupulous manufacturer of cheap handguns who the justice system was utterly incapable of holding accountable. So Red stepped in and delivered ‚Äújustice‚Äù in his signature way.</p>
<p>Director Cooper has warned Liz about how working with Red has made it increasingly difficult for them all to discern the line between right and wrong. But just as Liz seemed inclined to ‚Äòbe on Red‚Äôs side,‚Äô he now has a new reason to mistrust her. Of all the things he‚Äôs done, of all the lives taken and lost, what can he be hiding or who is he protecting that he would need to continue to keep the knowledge of his true identity from her at all costs?
</p></blockquote>
<p>&nbsp; </p>
<h3>‚≠ï Script 7:16 Nyle Hatcher (‚Ññ 149)</h3>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
[ 10 months ago ]<br />

Sheriff: Hey, Hatcher. Coroner&#8217;s finished with the scatter at the tree line. Probably got another seven or eight down there.<br />
Nyle Hatcher: So they&#8217;re released?<br />
Sheriff: Yep. All yours.<br />
Hatcher: [ Calls out ] The feds say we&#8217;re clear. Start bringing the victims up. Take a team to the tree line and start moving &#8217;em to the morgue.<br />
[ Camera shutter clicking ] [ Suspenseful music plays ] [ Hatcher flips through the pages of a profile of a man named Abraham Geller. He takes a photo of the face of one of the victims, a male ]</p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
[ People in Hazmat gear move bodies into a field morgue. A room is marked ‚ÄúIdentification.‚Äù Nyle Hatcher is working inside ]<br />
Tech: Here&#8217;s the next one, Hatcher.<br />
[ Hatcher pulls the sheet covering the dead man‚Äôs face ]<br />
Hatcher: Hello, Mr. Geller.<br />
[ Making sure he‚Äôs alone, Hatcher takes out a needle and syringe ]<br />
[ Indistinct conversations in distance ] </p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
[ Knock on door ] [ Nyle Hatcher opens the door. A young, pretty, blonde woman, smiles ]<br />
Young woman: Hey.<br />
Nyle Hatcher: Hello. You must be Crystal.<br />
Young woman: One and only. You look different than your profile picture.<br />
Hatcher: You look the same. Better. [ Chuckles lightly ] Please. Why don&#8217;t you come in.<br />
‚ãò‚ãô<br />
Young woman: I don&#8217;t understand. Over the phone, you said‚Äì<br />
Hatcher: I know what I said.<br />
Young woman: If you&#8217;re a cop‚Äì<br />
Hatcher: Please, I didn&#8217;t ask you here [ Inhales deeply ] for sex. Not like you think. It&#8217;s something different.<br />
Young woman: I&#8217;m leaving.<br />
Hatcher: Angela, sit down.<br />
Angela Hendrickson (young woman): How do you know my real name? Who are you?<br />
[ Ominous music plays ]<br />

<p>&nbsp;<br />
[ Dembe‚Äôs mosque ] [ Sadiq Asmal, Dembe‚Äôs imam, talks with Dembe and Red ]<br />

<b>Red:</b> Does he?<br />
Imam Asmal: I wouldn&#8217;t be much of a shepherd if I didn&#8217;t know the hearts and minds of my flock.<br />
[ Red‚Äôs cellphone rings ]<br />
<b>Red:</b> [ Sighs ] Excuse me. I&#8217;ll see what I can do.<br />
[ Ringing continues ] [ Red steps aside ] [ Beep ]<br />
<b>Red:</b> Is it done?<br />
Esi Jackson: [ On phone ] My job is to find people, not to keep them from being found.<br />
<b>Red:</b> Is it done?<br />
Jackson: It is. Wherever Koslov went, she&#8217;s never gonna find him.<br />
<b>Red:</b> Good. [ Beep ]<br />
‚ãò‚ãô<br />
[ Imam Asmal has left ]<br />

Dembe: Perhaps you should ask her. She&#8217;s waiting in the park. </p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
[ A park ] [ Birds chirping ]<br />
<b>Red:</b> You have a case.<br />
Liz: From my days in the Mobile Psych Unit. I&#8217;d like to dig into it.<br />
<b>Red:</b> If it&#8217;s important to you, then it&#8217;s important to me.<br />
Liz: You&#8217;re sure you don&#8217;t mind?<br />
<b>Red:</b>  Of course not. That&#8217;s what&#8217;s so nice about us finally being on the same side of things, same agenda. No subterfuge. What you want, I want.<br />
Liz: And you&#8217;re okay with my involving the team.<br />
<b>Red:</b> I am. In fact, I insist. Idle hands and all that. But I would like you to look into something for me.<br />

<b>Red:</b> It&#8217;s about Dembe&#8217;s‚Äì imam.<br />

<b>Red:</b> I don&#8217;t know yet. That&#8217;s what I need to find out. But first, tell me about this cold case of yours. </p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
[ The Post Office. Liz briefs the task force ]<br />
Liz: They called him the Boneyard Killer. His first victim was found just outside Rehoboth Beach when local police exhumed a body for autopsy. What they found was a second body buried in that same grave. A young woman four feet below the surface, resting just above a freshly buried coffin ‚Äì murdered and hidden in the last place anyone would ever look for her. Since then, three women have been discovered this way in graveyards in Virginia and West Virginia. He was using the cemeteries as dumpsites.<br />
Cooper: Anything significant about the graves that were chosen?<br />
Liz: They were fresh. Easy to dig.<br />
Agent Park: And the victims?<br />
Liz: All young women with a history of sex work.<br />
Aram: Okay, this is, uh, terrible, but sex workers are like 20 times more likely to be targeted by serial killers.<br />
Liz: True, but none of his victims were sexually assaulted, no sign of defensive wounds, no pre- or postmortem mutilation. But the way he killed them‚Äì we found dirt in their airways.<br />
Ressler: They were alive when he buried them.<br />
Liz: Alive, yes.<br />
‚ãò‚ãô<br />
[ Nyle Hatcher‚Äôs cellphone ringing. He turns it off ]<br />
‚ãò‚ãô<br />
Liz: And unconscious. Pumped so full of sodium thiopental, they&#8217;d never wake up.<br />
‚ãò‚ãô<br />
[ Hatcher places a vial on a table, and a medical clamp. He spreads out a large sheet of vinyl ]<br />
‚ãò‚ãô<br />
Park: I don&#8217;t understand. He drugged them so they&#8217;d die in their sleep? Why would he do that?<br />
Cooper: He didn&#8217;t want them to suffer.<br />
Liz: The case went cold until a week ago, when flash floods hit Montgomery and upended a few graves at Greenfare Cemetery, including one unidentified body that wasn&#8217;t supposed to be there. Initial forensics suggest she was sedated and buried alive just like the others.<br />
Cooper: Has the Bureau reached out to you?<br />
Liz: No, and they&#8217;re not going to. They asked me to leave the case. They said my profile wasn&#8217;t‚Äì additive.<br />
Ressler: So this is your cold case.<br />
Liz: Yes.<br />
Aram: What do you mean they thought your profile wasn&#8217;t &#8220;additive&#8221;?<br />
Liz: I don&#8217;t think he wants to kill. I think he&#8217;s mimicking these profiles in order to hide some other agenda. What, I don&#8217;t know, but I think he finds satisfaction in something other than the act of the crime itself.<br />
Cooper: Whatever his motive, these bodies were found by chance, and we can&#8217;t wait for another. Talk to the M.E. See what he knows. Let&#8217;s hope this newest tragedy will help you find this guy.<br />
[ They disperse, but Liz grabs Cooper ]<br />
Liz: Uh, sir, can I ask for another favor? Reddington says that counterterrorism is sniffing around Dembe&#8217;s imam.<br />
‚ãò‚ãô<br />
[ Imam Asmal bows down to pray ]<br />
‚ãò‚ãô<br />

Cooper: What were they looking for?<br />

[ Two men come up behind the imam, put a hood over his head and drag him off ]<br />
‚ãò‚ãô<br />

<p>&nbsp;<br />
[ Medical Examiner‚Äôs Office ] [ Waiting for the M.E., Liz talks to Ressler ]<br />
Liz: Ilya Koslov is out there somewhere, and I have no idea where.<br />
Ressler: Do you know what your mother wanted from him?<br />
Liz: I don&#8217;t. But she said her life depended on it.<br />
[ Door opens ]<br />
Medical Examiner: You were right. I looked at the original case files, and this does appear to be the work of the same killer. I have ID&#8217;d her as one Mara Lynne James. Now, the forensic evidence on your previous victims was limited, but this woman ‚Äì the cold slowed the growth of bacteria, so I have a better picture of what happened.<br />
Liz: Suffocation?<br />
M.E.: With sodium thiopental to sedate her beforehand. Soil in the lungs. Same lack of any defensive wounds.<br />
Liz: Was there any evidence of sexual assault?<br />
M.E.: No, but she was sexually active.<br />
[ He pulls back the sheet to reveal a c-section scar ]<br />
Liz: She had a baby.<br />
M.E.: The degree of scarring around the incision suggests she gave birth no more than a month before she was killed. </p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
[ Woman screaming ] [ Angela Hendrickson is in labor. She sits in a bathtub full of water. A Midwife is with her, as is Nyle Hatcher ]<br />
Midwife: Okay, now one more big push.<br />
Hatcher: C&#8217;mon. You can do it.<br />
Midwife: Come on. Push.<br />
Angela: [ Gasps ]<br />
[ Water sloshing ] [ The Midwife takes the baby ]<br />
Hatcher: You did it.<br />
Angela: Is everything okay? Isn&#8217;t he supposed to cry or some‚Äì<br />
[ Baby cries ]<br />
Midwife: Yes, she is. It&#8217;s a girl.<br />
‚ãò‚ãô<br />
[ The baby has been cleaned and dressed ] [ The Midwife gives the infant to Hatcher ]<br />
Hatcher: Rest. Please. [ To the baby ] We have work to do.<br />
[ Baby cries softly ] </p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
[ The home of the mother of Mara Lynne James, whose body had just been ID‚Äôd by the Medical Examiner. Mara‚Äôs sister Nancy is also there ]<br />
Mrs Margaret James: I tried to get her off the streets. We both did. We had every resource to help her.<br />
Agent Park: We apologize for coming at such a difficult time. We&#8217;re sorry for your loss.<br />

Nancy James: What for?<br />
Park: To find Mara&#8217;s child.<br />
Nancy: Mara didn&#8217;t have a child.<br />
Park: According to the M.E., she gave birth a month before she passed.<br />
Mrs James: A baby?<br />
Ressler: Did she have a man in her life?<br />
Nancy: <i>A</i> man? [ Scoffs ] You do know what she did for a living?<br />
Ressler: Did she talk about anyone in particular?<br />
Nancy: Yeah, she talked. She talked all the time. None of it was ever true.<br />
Mrs James: Nancy James, if you know something that could help that child‚Äì<br />
Nancy: [ Sighs ] A year ago ‚Äì 10 months maybe, she said she met a guy, [ Scoffs ] a big fish.<br />
Park: Did she tell you his name?<br />

One that I thought money could change. So I came up with a way to steal money from people that wouldn&#8217;t care that it was missing ‚Äì the dead. I like to think of them as &#8220;donors.&#8221; But the donors required hosts ‚Äì women who, sadly, needed to die to protect the plan ‚Äì which is why I chose women who needed to be freed from their otherwise insufferable lives. Finally, the plan requires a child.<br />

That upset me at first, until I realized that the money those children provided me wasn&#8217;t the solution. The children were the solution.<br />
Liz: What does that mean?<br />

<blockquote><p>
<b>Brief</b> (Where we‚Äôre at): Red has collapsed! Dembe has found him unconscious on the floor of the restaurant kitchen. Red and Dembe had just shared a meal with a group of Syrian refugees they had rescued while looking for Dembe‚Äôs Imam, Sadiq Asmal, who had been kidnapped.</p>
<p>Dembe had left Red for just a moment to answer a knock on the door. It was Red‚Äôs cleaner, Sakiya, who came to tell them she had found a fingerprint that might be connected nto Imam Asmal‚Äôs kidnapping ~ but it belongs to a man named Arturo Ruel who supposedly has been in prison for 15 years. When Dembe returned to the kitchen, Red was unconscious.</p>
<p>Red has a mysterious illness he has been hiding from Liz. He had funded the research of a brilliant pharmacist, Spalding Stark, and been treated by him, but the treatments turned out to be ineffective. Ressler saw Red‚Äôs medical file so he knows Red‚Äôs diagnosis, as does his friend (or relative?), Ilya Koslov (aka Frank Bloom).</p>
<p>Liz had been told by her grandfather, Dominic Wilkinson, that before Red took on the identity of her dead father, the real Raymond Reddington, he was named Ilya Koslov, but Liz found out from her mother that was not true. So she sicc‚Äôd a private investigator named Esi Jackson on Ilya. But Ilya became suspicious. Red had his interrogator Brimley question Esi Jackson and found out that Liz knows Red is not Ilya and that she is still determined to find out his true identity, his most guarded secret. </p>
<p>But Liz later confronted Jackson and Liz now knows Red knows she‚Äôs been investigating him ‚Äì just when he thought they were ‚Äúon the same side.‚Äù The real Ilya, meanwhile, has headed for the hills, to escape both Liz‚Äôs efforts and those of her mother, Katarina Rostova, who Liz knows is alive, but Red saw ‚Äúdie‚Äù in a staged assassination. </p>
<p>With her access to Ilya cut off, Katarina has turned to another source close to Red. It was she, in fact, who had Dembe‚Äôs imam kidnapped. What is Katarina looking for? Esi Jackson thinks she knows: </p>
<blockquote><p>
Esi Jackson: The Sikorsky Archive.<br />
Liz: What&#8217;s that?<br />
Jackson: Before Reddington warned me off, I had a mic trained on Ilya&#8217;s apartment. That archive, whatever it is, he&#8217;s obsessed with it. If Koslov has information that could save a woman&#8217;s life, my guess it&#8217;s in that archive.
</p></blockquote>
<p>Meanwhile, Ressler, who has been trying to ignore calls from his ‚Äúblack sheep‚Äù older brother Robby for days, was finally confronted by him in person. Robby informs Ressler that Ray Field is going to be excavated for a new strip mall and secrets of theirs buried there for decades will be unearthed.
</p></blockquote>
<p>&nbsp; </p>

<blockquote><p>
<b>Brief</b> (Where we‚Äôre at): ‚ÄúBoy Scout‚Äù Agent Ressler turned out out to have a past. As a teenager, he shot and (almost) killed his father‚Äôs Detroit PD officer partner, Tommy Markin, a dirty cop who Young Ressler found out had killed his father in a setup over kickbacks. But Markin was still alive and it was his older brother Robby who had delivered the final blow, before burying him in a place called Ray Field. 25 years later, with Ray Field scheduled for excavation, Ressler returned to help Robby dig up Markin‚Äôs body, only to have car with the skeleton stolen by mobsters with whom Robby had become ensnared. They planned to come clean and reached out to Liz, who helped capture the mobsters but had other ideas about whether Ressler and Robby should turn themselves in. </p>
<p>Liz told Ressler how much she relied on him as an ‚Äúisland of calm‚Äù in her ‚ÄúFEMA disaster of a life.‚Äù The scene ended with a hug ‚Ä¶ </p>
<p><i>[ Since the last episode stepped out of the overall story arc, below is where the rest of the plot stood at the end of the previous episode, 7:16 Nyle Hatcher: ]</i></p>
<p>Red had collapsed. Red and Dembe had just shared a meal with a group of Syrian refugees they had rescued while looking for Dembe‚Äôs Imam, Sadiq Asmal, who had been kidnapped.</p>
<p>Dembe had left Red for just a moment to answer a knock on the door. It was Red‚Äôs cleaner, Sakiya, who had come to tell them she had found a fingerprint that might be connected nto Imam Asmal‚Äôs kidnapping ~ but it belongs to a man named Arturo Ruel who has been in prison for 15 years. When Dembe returned to the kitchen, Red was unconscious.</p>
<p>Red has a mysterious illness he has been hiding from Liz. He had funded the research of a brilliant pharmacist, Spalding Stark, and been treated by him, but the treatments turned out to be ineffective. Ressler saw Red‚Äôs medical file so he knows Red‚Äôs diagnosis, as does his friend (or relative?), Ilya Koslov (aka Frank Bloom).</p>
<p>Liz had been told by her grandfather, Dominic Wilkinson, that before Red took on the identity of her dead father, the real Raymond Reddington, he was named Ilya Koslov, but Liz found out from her mother that was not true. So she sic‚Äôd a private investigator named Esi Jackson on Ilya. But Ilya became suspicious. Red had his interrogator Brimley question Esi Jackson and found out that Liz knows Red is not Ilya and that she is still determined to find out his true identity, his most guarded secret. </p>
<p>Liz later confronted Jackson and Liz now knows Red knows she‚Äôs been investigating him ‚Äì just when he thought they were ‚Äúon the same side.‚Äù The real Ilya, meanwhile, has headed for the hills, to escape both Liz‚Äôs pursuit and that of her mother, Katarina Rostova, who Liz knows is alive, but Red saw ‚Äúdie‚Äù in a staged assassination. </p>
<p>With her access to Ilya cut off, Katarina has turned to another source close to Red. It was she, in fact, who had Dembe‚Äôs Imam kidnapped. What is Katarina looking for? Esi Jackson thinks she knows: </p>
<blockquote><p>
Esi Jackson: The Sikorsky Archive.<br />
Liz: What&#8217;s that?<br />
Jackson: Before Reddington warned me off, I had a mic trained on Ilya&#8217;s apartment. That archive, whatever it is, he&#8217;s obsessed with it. If Koslov has information that could save a woman&#8217;s life, my guess it&#8217;s in that archive.
</p></blockquote>
</blockquote>

<h2>üî¥ Script 7:19 Kazanjian Brothers (‚Ññ 156-157)</h2>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
Program air date: 5/15/2020 in the US<br />
Script Permalink: <a href="https://wp.me/pDKwi-arR" rel="nofollow">https://wp.me/pDKwi-arR</a><br />
Entertainment Weekly Recap: <a href="http://bit.ly/3fR3VeB" rel="nofollow">http://bit.ly/3fR3VeB</a><br />
&nbsp; </p></div>
<div align="center">‡º∫‚ú¶ ‚ô§ ‚ú¶‡ºª</div>
<div align="left">
&nbsp;<br />
<b>Director:</b> Michael <b> Caracciolo </b><br />
<b>Written by:</b> Kelli <b>Johnson</b>, Sam <b>Christopher</b></p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
<img loading="lazy" data-attachment-id="40207" data-permalink="https://blacklistdeclassified.net/%f0%9f%94%b4-ye-olde-photo-workshoppe/a319c075-3de7-41c3-95fd-b68e494a08b4/" &nbsp; </p>
<blockquote><p>
<b>Technical Note:</b> Episode 7:19 is the finale of Season 7 of The Blacklist which was shortened due to the pandemic caused by COVID-19, which shut down both New York City and Los Angeles, where the series is filmed and produced. The final episode was not completely filmed when production halted. In addition, the death of Brian Dennehy, who played Liz‚Äôs grandfather, Dominic Wilkinson, means his character has to be written out of the story. Word is that the episode was to be pieced together out of scenes that were already filmed, flashback scenes, and animated scenes with the voices dubbed in. As the saying goes, ‚ÄúNecessity is the Mother of Invention.‚Äù<br />
&nbsp;<br />
<font color="red"><b>Brief</b> (Where we‚Äôre at):</font> Red is suffering from a mysterious illness and is making arrangements to pass his assets to Liz, a proposition she says she won‚Äôt agree to. Katarina Rostova, Liz‚Äôs mother, seems determined to beat Mother Nature to Red, telling Liz, ‚ÄúI don&#8217;t think one of us can live while the other survives‚Äù:</p>
<blockquote><p>
Katarina: ‚Ä¶ [T]here will be ‚Äì more choices for you to make.<br />
Liz: Between you and him.
</p></blockquote>
<p>Liz, it turns out, has been collaborating with Katarina (who Red had thought was dead) in her effort to determine who Red really is ‚Äì or was ‚Äì before he took on the identity of Raymond Reddington, Liz‚Äôs dead father, a question Katarina also wants answered. Dembe found out Liz was involved in the kidnapping of his imam, but did not tell Red. He also admitted to Red that although he did not divulge the secret of Red‚Äôs identity, he would have done to save his imam‚Äôs life ‚Äì had Red had not shown up in the nick of time:</p>
<blockquote><p>
<b><b>Red:</b></b> [ To Dembe ] Did you tell her anything?<br />
Dembe: No. But I was going to.
</p></blockquote>
<p>As Red told Imam Asmal, ‚ÄúDembe and I have done this dance before. I made it clear there wouldn&#8217;t be an encore.‚Äù </p>
<p>Dembe has betrayed Red twice: by almost betraying his identity to Katarina and by keeping from him the fact that it was Liz who had arranged for the imam‚Äôs kidnapping. Will Dembe pay a price for his failure of loyalty? And why, in light of all this, and knowing that Liz had hired a private investigator to delve into his past, is Red ready to turn over everything to her? Cryptically, he explains to Marvin Gerard, his lawyer:</p>
<blockquote><p>
Marvin Gerard: You&#8217;re giving a cop the keys to your kingdom.<br />
<b><b>Red:</b></b> Regrettably.<br />
Gerard: Why do it?<br />
<b><b>Red:</b></b> Because where she&#8217;s going, she&#8217;ll need it.<br />
Gerard: And where, pray tell, is our plucky heroine going?<br />
<b><b>Red:</b></b> To a very dark and dangerous place.
</p></blockquote>
</blockquote>
<p>&nbsp; </p>
<h3>‚≠ï Script 7:19 Kazanjian Brothers (‚Ññ 156-157)</h3>
